<exercise xml:id="Ez_9_8_2">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Let <m>y = f(x)</m> define a curve in the plane. We can consider this curve as a curve in three-space with <m>z</m>-coordinate 0.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find a parameterization of the form <m>\vr(t) = \langle x(t), y(t), z(t) \rangle</m> of the curve <m>y=f(x)</m> in three-space.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        If we let <m>x(t) = t</m>, then <m>y(t) = f(t)</m> and <m>z(t)=0</m>. So a parameterization of the curve defined by <m>y=f(x)</m> is
        <md>
          \vr(t) = \langle t, f(t), 0 \rangle
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use the formula
        <md>
          \kappa = \frac{\lvert \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) \rvert}{\lvert \vr'(t) \rvert^3}
        </md>
        to show that
        <md>
          \kappa = \frac{\lvert f''(x) \rvert}{\left[1+(f'(x))^2\right]^{3/2}}.
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since
        <md>
          \vr'(t) = \vi + f'(t) \vj \text{ and }  \vr''(t) = f''(t) \vj
        </md>,
        we have
        <md>
          \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) = f''(t) \vk
        </md>.
        So
        <md>
          <mrow>\kappa \amp = \frac{\lvert \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) \rvert}{\lvert \vr'(t) \rvert^3}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{\lvert f''(t) \rvert}{\sqrt{1+(f'(t))^2}^3}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{\lvert f''(t) \rvert}{\left[1+(f'(t))^2\right]^{3/2}}</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="Ez_9_8_3">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Consider the single variable function defined by <m>y = 4x^2 - x^3.</m>
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find a parameterization of the form <m>\vr(t) = \langle x(t), y(t) \rangle</m> that traces the curve <m>y = 4x^2 - x^3</m> on the interval from <m>x =  -3</m> to <m>x = 3</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        If we let <m>x(t) = t</m>, then <m>y(t) = 4t^2-t^3</m>. So a parameterization of the curve on the interval from <m>x =  -3</m> to <m>x = 3</m> is
        <md>
          \vr(t) = \langle t, 4t^2-t^3 \rangle
        </md>
        for <m>t</m> in <m>[-3,3]</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Write a definite integral which, if evaluated, gives the exact length of the given curve from <m>x =  -3</m> to <m>x = 3</m>.  Why is the integral difficult to evaluate exactly?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The length of the curve for <m>x =  -3</m> to <m>x = 3</m> is given by the integral
        <md>
          \int_{-3}^{3} \vecmag{\vr'(t)} \, dt = \int_{-3}^3 \sqrt{1+(8t-3t^2)^2} \, dt
        </md>.
        The sum under the root makes this integral difficult to evaluate exactly.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>       
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Determine the curvature, <m>\kappa(t)</m>, of the parameterized curve. (<xref ref="Ez_9_8_2">Exercise</xref> might be useful here.)
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The curvature <m>\kappa(t)</m> can be calculated using the formula from <xref ref="Ez_9_8_2">Exercise</xref>. Since <m>f'(x) = 8x - 3x^2</m> and <m>f''(x) = 8-6x</m>, we have
        <md>
          \kappa(t) = \frac{ \lvert 8-6t \rvert }{ \left[1+(8t-3t^2)^2\right]^{3/2} }
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use appropriate technology to approximate the absolute maximum and minimum of <m>\kappa(t)</m> on the parameter interval for your parameterization.  Compare your results with the graph of <m>y = 4x^2 - x^3</m>.  How do the absolute maximum and absolute minimum of <m>\kappa(t)</m> align with the original curve?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        A plot of <m>\kappa(t)</m> on the interval <m>[-3,3]</m> shows relative maxima near 0 and 2.8. A computer algebra system shows that <m>\frac{ 8-6t  }{ \left[1+(8t-3t^2)^2\right]^{3/2} }</m> has critical numbers at approximately <m>-0.003881710157</m> and <m>2.670548377</m>. Now
        <md>
          \kappa(-0.003881710157) \approx  8.011664828 \text{ and }  \kappa(2.670548377) \approx 8.011664851
        </md>,
        so the maximum value of <m>\kappa</m> on <m>[-3,3]</m> is approximately 8.011664851. The minimum value of <m>\kappa</m> must occur at an endpoint.
        Since
        <md>
          \kappa(-3) \approx 0.0001958900647 \text{ and }  \kappa(3) \approx 0.3162277660
        </md>,
        the minimum value of <m>\kappa</m> on <m>[-3,3]</m> is approximately 0.0001958900647. The graph of <m>y=4x^2-x^3</m> is close to linear at <m>x=-3</m>, which accounts for the low value of <m>\kappa</m> there. The largest curvature in the graph is  just after the critical point at <m>x = \frac{8}{3} \approx 2.666</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="Ez_9_8_5">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this exercise we verify the curvature formula
      <md>
        \kappa = \frac{\lvert \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) \rvert}{\lvert \vr'(t) \rvert^3}.
      </md>
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Explain why
        <md>
          \lvert \vr'(t) \rvert = \frac{ds}{dt}.
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We showed that <m>\frac{d \vr}{ds} = 1</m>, so the Chain Rule shows that
        <md>
          \lvert \frac{d \vr}{dt} \rvert = \lvert \frac{d \vr}{ds} \frac{ds}{dt} \rvert = \lvert \frac{d \vr}{ds} \rvert \lvert \frac{ds}{dt} \rvert = \lvert \frac{ds}{dt} \rvert = \frac{ds}{dt}
        </md>,
        since <m>s</m> is an increasing function.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use the fact that <m>\vT(t) = \frac{\vr'(t)}{\lvert \vr'(t) \rvert}</m> and <m>\lvert \vr'(t) \rvert = \frac{ds}{dt}</m> to explain why
        <md>
          \vr'(t) = \frac{ds}{dt} \vT(t).
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Note that
        <md>
          \vr'(t) = \lvert \vr'(t) \rvert \vT(t) = \frac{ds}{dt} \vT(t)
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The Product Rule shows that
        <md>
          \vr''(t) = \frac{d^2s}{dt^2} \vT(t) + \frac{ds}{dt} \vT'(t).
        </md>
        Explain why
        <md>
          \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) = \left(\frac{ds}{dt}\right)^2 (\vT(t) \times \vT'(t)).
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Using the previous results we see that
        <md>
          <mrow>\vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) \amp = \left( \frac{ds}{dt} \vT(t) \right) \times \left( \frac{d^2s}{dt^2} \vT(t) + \frac{ds}{dt} \vT'(t) \right)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \left( \frac{ds}{dt} \vT(t) \times \frac{d^2s}{dt^2} \vT(t) \right) + \left( \frac{ds}{dt} \vT(t) \times \frac{ds}{dt} \vT'(t) \right)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \left( \frac{ds}{dt} \right) \left( \frac{d^2s}{dt^2} \right) \left( \vT(t) \times \vT(t) \right) + \left( \frac{ds}{dt} \right) \left( \frac{ds}{dt} \right) \left( \vT(t) \times \vT'(t) \right)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \left(\frac{ds}{dt}\right)^2 (\vT(t) \times \vT'(t))</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="TdotNzero" text="custom">Key Idea</xref> on <m>\vT</m> and <m>\vN</m> we showed that <m>\lvert \vT(t) \rvert = 1</m> implies that <m>\vT(t)</m> is orthogonal to <m>\vT'(t)</m> for every value of <m>t</m>. Explain what this tells us about <m>\lvert \vT(t) \times \vT'(t) \rvert</m> and conclude that
        <md>
          \lvert \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) \rvert = \left(\frac{ds}{dt}\right)^2 \lvert \vT'(t) \rvert.
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We know that
        <md>
          \vT(t) \times \vT'(t) = \lvert \vT(t) \rvert \lvert \vT'(t) \rvert \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) \vn
        </md>
        for some unit vector <m>\vn</m> orthogonal to both <m>\vT(t)</m> and <m>\vT'(t)</m>.
        So
        <md>
          \lvert \vT(t) \times \vT'(t) \rvert = \lvert \vT(t) \rvert \lvert \vT'(t) \rvert \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) \lvert \vn \rvert = \lvert \vT'(t) \rvert
        </md>.
        It follows that
        <md>
          \lvert \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) \rvert = \left(\frac{ds}{dt}\right)^2 \lvert \vT(t) \times \vT'(t) \rvert = \left(\frac{ds}{dt}\right)^2 \lvert \vT'(t) \rvert
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Finally, use the fact that <m>\kappa = \frac{\lvert \vT'(t) \rvert }{\lvert \vr'(t) \rvert}</m> to verify that
        <md>
          \kappa = \frac{\lvert \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) \rvert}{\lvert \vr'(t) \rvert^3}.
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We have
        <md>
          \lvert \vT'(t) \rvert = \frac{\lvert \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) \rvert}{\left(\frac{ds}{dt}\right)^2}
        </md>
        and so
        <md>
          <mrow>\kappa \amp = \frac{\lvert \vT'(t) \rvert }{\lvert \vr'(t) \rvert}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{\lvert \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) \rvert }{\left(\frac{ds}{dt}\right)^2 \lvert \vr'(t) \rvert}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{\lvert \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) \rvert }{\left( \lvert \vr'(t) \rvert \right)^2 \lvert \vr'(t) \rvert}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{\lvert \vr'(t) \times \vr''(t) \rvert}{\lvert \vr'(t) \rvert^3}</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="Ez_9_8_6">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this exercise we explore how to find the osculating circle for a given curve. As an example, we will use the curve defined by <m>f(x) = x^2</m>. Recall that this curve can be parameterized by <m>x(t) = t</m> and <m>y(t)=t^2</m>. 
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use <xref ref="def-unit-tangent"/> to find <m>\vT(t)</m> for our function <m>f</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        To find the center of the osculating circle, we will want to find a vector that points from a point on the curve to the center of the circle. Such a vector will be orthogonal to the tangent vector at that point. Recall that <m>\vT(s) = \langle \cos(\phi(s)), \sin(\phi(s)) \rangle</m>, where <m>\phi</m> is the angle the tangent vector to the curve makes with a horizontal vector. Use this fact to show that 
                  <md> \vT \cdot \frac{dT}{ds} = 0.
                  </md>
                  Explain why this tells us that <m>\frac{dT}{ds}</m> is orthogonal to <m>\vT</m>. Let <m>\vN</m> be the unit vector in the direction of <m>\frac{dT}{ds}</m>. The vector <m>\vN</m> is called the <em>principal unit normal vector</em><idx><h>principal unit normal vector</h></idx> and points in the direction toward which the curve is turning. The vector <m>\vN</m> also points toward the center of the osculating circle.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find <m>\vT</m> at the point <m>(1,1)</m> on the graph of <m>f</m>. Then find <m>\vN</m> at this same point. How do you know you have the correct direction for <m>\vN</m>? 
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <sidebyside widths="50% 50%" margins="0%">
        <p>
          Let <m>P</m> be a point on the curve. Recall that <m>\rho = \frac{1}{\kappa}</m> at point <m>P</m> is the radius of the osculating circle at point <m>P</m>. We call <m>\rho</m> the <em>radius of curvature</em><idx><h>radius of curvature</h></idx> at point <m>P</m>. Let <m>C</m> be the center of the osculating circle to the curve at point <m>P</m>, and let <m>O</m> be the origin. Let <m>\mathbf{\gamma}</m> be the vector <m>\overrightarrow{OC}</m>. See <xref ref="F-9-8-osculating-center">Figure</xref> for an illustration using an arbitrary function <m>f</m>.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="F-9-8-osculating-center">
        <caption>An osculating circle.</caption>
        <image width="30%" source="images/fig_9_8_osculating_center"><description><p>An osculating circle.</p>
        </description></image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
      
          Which vector, in terms of <m>\rho</m> and <m>\vN</m> points from the point <m>P</m> to the point <m>C</m>? Use this vector to explain why 
        <md>
          \mathbf{\gamma} = \vr + \rho \vN,
        </md>
        where <m>\vr = \overrightarrow{OP}</m>.   
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Finally, use the previous work to find the center of the osculating circle for <m>f</m> at the point <m>(1,1)</m>. Draw pictures of the curve and the osculating circle to verify your work.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>    
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="ez-VVF-curvature-line">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="act-VVF-curvature-line-circle"/>, you verified for a <em>specific</em> line that the curvature is <m>0</m>. The generalization of this is that the unit speed parameterization of a line through <m>(x_0,y_0,z_0)</m> with direction vector <m>\langle a,b,c\rangle</m> can be given by 
    <md>
      <mrow>  \vr(s)\amp =\langle x(s),y(s),z(s) \rangle</mrow>
      <mrow>  \amp= \left\langle x_0+\frac{a}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}}s , y_0+\frac{b}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2}}s ,z_0+  \frac{c}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}}s\right\rangle</mrow>
    </md>.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Compute the speed of this parameterization to verify that this has unit speed. This will also show that <m>\vr\, '(s)=\vv(s)=\vT(s)</m> (which is not true in general).
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Calculating the derivative of the parameterization gives 
        <md>\vr'(t) = \left\langle \frac{a}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}} , \frac{b}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2}} ,  \frac{c}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}}\right\rangle</md>
        which has length 1. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Calculate <m>\vT(s)</m>, <m>\frac{d\vT}{ds}</m>, and <m>\vecmag{ \frac{d\vT}{ds} }</m> for this unit speed parameterization of a line.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>\vT(s) = \left\langle \frac{a}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}} , \frac{b}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2}} ,  \frac{c}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}}\right\rangle </md> which has a derivative of the zero vector because <m>\vT(s)</m> does not depend on <m>s</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Write a few sentences to explain why your result for the calculation of the curvature of a line makes sense in general.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        As mentioned eariler, the curvature of a straight line is zero and the radius of curvature would be undefined. There is not a radius of curvature because there is no turning happening along the straightaway list.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\vu \times \vw = \vzero</m>, what does this say about the direction of <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vw</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          If <m>\vu \times \vw = \vzero</m>, then <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vw</m> will be parallel to each other. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Remember that the vector <m>\vv</m> has magnitude and direction, so the derivative <m>\frac{d\vv}{dt} = \va</m> will measure the change in both the magnitude and direction of of <m>\vv</m>. Write a few sentences to describe how if <m>\vv</m> and <m>\va= \frac{d\vv}{dt}</m> are in parallel directions, then the unit normal vector will be undefined at that point.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          If <m>\vv</m> and <m>\va= \frac{d\vv}{dt}</m> are in parallel directions, then all of the change in <m>\vv</m> is in the direction of motion. This means there cannot be any turning happening at this instant and thus the unit normal vector (which measures the direction of turning) will be undefined.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    
  </exercise>

